metadata.name: Valley of Empty Future #43
metadata.description:
*translated from drone swarm operator 51b13*
Preliminary analysis of the planet's atmosphere suggest an increased concentration of carbon monoxide, consistent with temperature readings.
No fauna or flora detected on immediate surface. Even though soil spectroscopy confirm presence of organic compounds, samples must be collected in order to have definitive results.

Scouts have confirmed, trough x-ray and radar imaging, sprawling areas of artificial environments. High density of buildings suggest an intricate and highly developed societal structure, with only it's tallest buildings piercing trough the meters deep silicate dust covering most of the area. It intrigues me why build so high, would these be religious monuments to be seen by all, for their exuberance? Immediately forwarding digital reconstruction of the -cities?- for Cosmic Sociologists to further speculate on their purposes.

////

On fullscreen view, press P to download a 1920*2560 PNG

Made in Cables.gl

metadata.name: Particularization #104
metadata.description:
“Particularization” is the seventh collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

All concepts can be viewed from different levels. You can focus on the details, leaving out the generalized result but understanding the finer points. Or you could emphasize the concept as a whole, comprehending it well overall but missing out on the specifics. It's impossible to choose both, you have to figure out which approach works best for each scenario.

metadata.name: WTBS Logo with Friends #199
metadata.description:
Did you know that WTBS is now sixth months old? If we were Will’s baby, we’d be sitting up and prepping to crawl — the literal baby steps that precede an entire lifetime of movement. 

Play is another integral part of our development. Play teaches us to connect, laugh, share, love, and learn. It helps form our earliest friendships that mold us into who we are destined to become. Over the last six months we have had the immense pleasure of forming new relationships with some of the amazing artists that comprise of the fxhash community. 

It is the love and support of new friends Laurent Houdard, Ada Ada Ada, elsif, and Camille Roux that made our first (official) collaboration possible. Thank you so much for the idea, the vision, the art, the time, and the wrangling to make this possible. 

Each letter is imbued with the unique style of an artist, based on a framework created by Laurent. There is a small chance of receiving a piece with two of the same style, with the rarest possibility of receiving one with all four quadrants the same. 

Collect with love and the knowledge that your support means the world to us. Thank you for listening every week, and for the messages and stories that you share with us. We can’t wait to continue to grow.

Thank you so much again to Laurent, Ada, elsif, and Camille. This is what community is.

metadata.name: Alpinism #23
metadata.description:
“Only those who will risk going too far can possibly find out how far one can go.” - T.S. Eliot

---

Alpinism is a tribute to the rugged and wild landscapes that rise around us. Which may at once intrigue, impress, intimidate, and inspire.

I am captivated by the mythology of these settings. Where natural shapes appear fantastical. A ridge line drawn by pen meets sky poured out from neon gradient. Where observation is made through the lens of imagination.

Each piece begins with the concept of a mountain landscape. A number of ranges are drawn by pen in one of three styles. Within each style is a spectrum of variation that produces different drawn qualities. The backdrop may be an imagined sky, an impossible sunset, a piece of parchment. A testament to the interpreter’s memory of the scene. 

---
- Made with p5js in the White Mountains of NH July 2022
- press s to save png

metadata.name: Alleles #52
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

metadata.name: Moving Blocks Mono #47
metadata.description:
Moving blocks formed by moving blocks.

How does it work?

Several shapes form boundaries. Within these boundaries, the moving blocks move pixels and rotate their color values from a specific color
to black.
Each shape has its own direction vector, which affects the feature-based directions and speed of the moving blocks.

Features:

- 109 colors: one from a unified color list (based on W3C SVG 1.0 color keyword names)
- 3, 5 or 7 shapes: 3 different sizes and 2 types (quads and circles)
- 1 - 3 clusters: shapes are assigned round-robin
- 10 rotation angles: from -168° to 168
- 5 grid sizes: based on Fibonacci numbers, starting with 377, block size is always 21
- Movable blocks: based on grid size (one Fibonacci number before)
- 127 directions of movement: based on 8 basic directions (up, up, left, left-up, left-down, right, right-up, right-down), limited to the 3,
  4, 8
  long combinations
- 2 behavior modes for movement distance: negative = decreasing and limited by range or shape, positive = increasing and limited by shape

Animation and feature selection are based on the deterministic prng XorShift128 seeded with the fxhash. This allows repeated playback in the
same order.

The size is fixed at 1980x1980 pixels.

The preview images are taken after 900 frames.

The animation will stop automatically at 900 frames. Press spacebar, click mouse or touch to change pausing. You can add `autopause` as
query string parameter to disable automatic pausing.

Press `c` to capture an image. Press `f` for fullscreen. Press `h` to see all options.

metadata.name: Circinus #1
metadata.description:
Hey, planet Earth!

I've been working on this piece for a while now. It's a little bit of modern art, and a whole lot of space. I wanted to bring you into the Milky Way—and then we realized how much fun it would be to bring you into the galaxy.

Our piece is an homage to the stars and planets that make up our beautiful universe—we hope it inspires you to look up at night, and appreciate what we have here on Earth.

metadata.name: Millefoglie #408
metadata.description:
"A mille-feuille (French pronunciation: ​[mil fœj], "thousand-sheets"), also known by the names Napoleon, vanilla slice, and custard slice, is a dessert made of puff pastry layered with pastry cream. Its modern form was influenced by improvements made by Marie-Antoine Carême.

Traditionally, a mille-feuille is made up of three layers of puff pastry (pâte feuilletée), alternating with two layers of pastry cream (crème pâtissière). The top pastry layer is finished in various ways: sometimes it is topped with whipped cream, or it may be dusted with icing sugar, cocoa, pastry crumbs, or sliced almonds. It may also be glazed with icing or fondant alone, or in alternating white (icing) and brown (chocolate) or other colored icing stripes, and combed to create a marbled effect." — Wikipedia

Prints available upon request: prints@stefancontiero.com
Best enjoyed on browsers supporting Display-P3 color gamut.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0
